## Context
New references requested by the referees. QUICK to add as verified bib entries;
integration into prose lives in the content tickets (0139/0141; 0135 disconnected 2026-07-08 — Golka not integrated there). Validate
every entry (DOI/venue) before adding — do not fabricate metadata.

## Actions — add to bibliography/main.bib (verified)
1. Golka (2024), "Epistemic Gerrymandering: ESG, Impact Investing, and the Financial Governance of Sustainability," Review of International Political Economy, 31:6, 1894–1918. (R1 §1)
2. Escobar — DONE: escobar1995 + escobar1988 added (both picked, verified on PDFs).
3. Mitchell, Timothy — DONE: mitchell2002 + mitchell1998 added (both picked, verified on PDFs).
4. King & Levine (1993) — finance-development nexus. (R1 add'l)
5. Aghion & Bolton — finance-development. (R1 add'l)
6. Star & Griesemer (1989), "Institutional Ecology, 'Translations' and
   Boundary Objects…", Social Studies of Science 19(3) — canonical
   definition, engaged head-on in the conclusion (brief
   `boundary-object-conceded-then-displaced`, 0171).
7. Star (2010), "This is Not a Boundary Object", Science, Technology &
   Human Values 35(5) — the standardisation/infrastructure dynamic the
   displacement relies on (same brief entry, 0171).

## Discussion Escobar/Mitchell — SOLE HOME of this discussion (author decision pending)

This ticket carries the works-selection discussion entirely and exclusively
(author directive 2026-07-08). Hold it here or in a session opened on this
ticket; other tickets only point here (0133 child list; 0152 row R2.30).
Prose integration afterwards stays in the content tickets (0141 owns the
passage).

**The remark (R2.30, verbatim from the 0152 table):** « Desrosières/Porter
may not be the best refs for biased aid architectures — engage Escobar,
Tim Mitchell. »

**Manuscript anchor:** the biased-aid-architectures passage and the
Desrosières quote (p7 of v1; in the v2.0.5 base, the DAC statistical-
conventions paragraph, §1 development-economics tradition). The question:
do Escobar/Mitchell *replace* Desrosières/Porter there, or complement them
(construction-of-categories lineage vs postcolonial critique of the
development apparatus)?

**Candidate works to discuss** (canonical shortlist; verify DOI/venue
before any entry — do not fabricate):
- Escobar, *Encountering Development: The Making and Unmaking of the Third
  World*, Princeton UP, 1995 — the reference critique of development as a
  discursive apparatus.
- Escobar, "Power and Visibility: Development and the Invention and
  Management of the Third World," *Cultural Anthropology* 3(4), 1988 —
  article-length alternative if the book is too broad.
- Mitchell, *Rule of Experts: Egypt, Techno-Politics, Modernity*, U. of
  California Press, 2002 — expertise making "the economy" governable.
- Mitchell, "Fixing the Economy," *Cultural Studies* 12(1), 1998 — the
  economy as a constructed object; closest fit to the paper's
  object-construction thesis.
- Mitchell, *Carbon Democracy*, Verso, 2011 — energy/politics angle;
  probably too far from the aid-architecture passage.

**Disambiguation:** do not confuse Timothy Mitchell with Ian Mitchell
(CGD), whose 2021 note "Is Climate Finance Really New and Additional?"
appears in `docs/ai-tech-reports/Climate_Finance_Annotated_Bibliography.md`
— the CGD note is relevant to additionality (R2 elsewhere), not to this
remark.

